00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:14.531
You want to see what kind of statistical studies

00:00:14.531 --> 00:00:17.937
can you perform to better understand sugar intake in

00:00:17.937 --> 00:00:21.120
the population generally and whether that seems

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:24.405
to be causing heart disease in some way.

00:00:24.405 --> 00:00:26.312
Well, the first that you might want to do is just to try

00:00:26.312 --> 00:00:30.414
to get a sense of sugar intake in the population as a whole.

00:00:30.414 --> 00:00:33.060
Now clearly, you don't know know, there's no way

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:36.889
of measuring exactly how much sugar every member, let's say

00:00:36.889 --> 00:00:38.440
you're talking about the United States, every member

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:42.579
of that 300 million population is consuming everyday.

00:00:42.579 --> 00:00:45.188
The way that we try to get a sense of how much sugar

00:00:45.188 --> 00:00:48.995
is being consumed is by conducting a sample study.

00:00:48.995 --> 00:00:53.566
So you take your population, your 300 million people.

00:00:53.566 --> 00:00:57.844
So you take your population right over here.

00:00:57.844 --> 00:00:59.832
Population.

00:00:59.832 --> 00:01:01.826
And you sample it.

00:01:01.826 --> 00:01:04.849
You sample your population and not only

00:01:04.849 --> 00:01:06.678
do you sample it, but you randomly sample it.

00:01:06.678 --> 00:01:09.825
Obviously you don't want to just survey people who are

00:01:09.825 --> 00:01:13.229
exiting a cupcake store or people who are exiting a gym.

00:01:13.229 --> 00:01:16.335
You want it to be a random sample of people,

00:01:16.335 --> 00:01:20.218
where where you're sampling them shouldn't somehow

00:01:20.218 --> 00:01:23.294
affect whether or not their answer or how much sugar

00:01:23.294 --> 00:01:25.673
they might say that they are consuming.

00:01:25.673 --> 00:01:27.441
But they are gonna tell you how much sugar

00:01:27.441 --> 00:01:30.067
they consume, let's say, on an average day maybe

00:01:30.067 --> 00:01:32.880
by filling out a survey or through some other way.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:36.303
And through that you would take this data and obviously,

00:01:36.303 --> 00:01:38.266
the more samples you have the better and we talk

00:01:38.266 --> 00:01:40.345
about that in depth in other statistics videos.

00:01:40.345 --> 00:01:44.913
About how you get a better predictor of the actual true

00:01:44.913 --> 00:01:48.922
population parameter, the more samples that you might take.

00:01:48.922 --> 00:01:52.345
But you might do that to get a gauge of how much sugar

00:01:52.345 --> 00:01:55.847
the average American consumes in a given day.

00:01:55.847 --> 00:01:59.276
So this right over here where you are taking random samples

00:01:59.276 --> 00:02:03.129
of the population to, essentially, generate a statistic

00:02:03.129 --> 00:02:07.389
that is estimating a true parameter, which is the actual

00:02:07.389 --> 00:02:11.181
amount of sugar Americans are consuming each day.

00:02:11.181 --> 00:02:13.396
We call this a sample study.

00:02:14.027 --> 00:02:17.338
Sample study.

00:02:17.338 --> 00:02:19.746
It's a way, once again, of just estimating what the

00:02:19.746 --> 00:02:23.407
actual amount of sugar people are having each day.

00:02:23.407 --> 00:02:24.806
Let's say you want to go further.

00:02:24.806 --> 00:02:27.952
This will give you a sense of what is likely the amount

00:02:27.952 --> 00:02:30.702
of sugar that people are consuming each day, but you

00:02:30.702 --> 00:02:33.726
really want to see how that's related to heart disease.

00:02:33.726 --> 00:02:37.501
So instead, what you do is you go survey people.

00:02:37.501 --> 00:02:43.499
You go survey people and you say, "How much sugar have

00:02:43.499 --> 00:02:46.703
"you consumed over", and once again, when you pick

00:02:46.703 --> 00:02:49.706
these people, you should be doing it randomly.

00:02:49.706 --> 00:02:54.477
So let's say you go survey a random sample of 60 year olds.

00:02:54.477 --> 00:02:56.530
So once again, you wouldn't want to sample people

00:02:56.530 --> 00:02:58.832
who are in the hospital, you wouldn't want to

00:02:58.832 --> 00:03:03.066
sample people who are at or just at the gym.

00:03:03.066 --> 00:03:04.702
You would want to find a random sample

00:03:04.702 --> 00:03:06.796
or sample them in places where it shouldn't

00:03:06.796 --> 00:03:09.289
affect their answer, which way they are going to go.

00:03:09.289 --> 00:03:14.644
Let's say you surveyed 300 60 year olds and you asked them

00:03:14.644 --> 00:03:18.594
how much sugar have they consumed over the last 30 years.

00:03:18.594 --> 00:03:21.810
And you also asked them their condition of their heart.

00:03:21.810 --> 00:03:24.027
And what you get is something like this.

